<div class="sub-content-header">Changing the Way We Hear Things</div>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<i><span class="smallText">Jan 09, 2009 12:35:22</span></i>

<br /><br />

If you've been following CES this past month, it's likely you've also been following <A href="/news/30daysInnovation.asp">30 Days of Innovation: A Countdown to CES</A>, which offers a daily profile of one new-to-CES exhibitor. One month and one huge stack of cool products later, the countdown continues on. In fact, we're serving up four bonus exhibitors during show days.&nbsp;If you still don't feel like your need for new technology is sated, then get to the show floor to discover what's new and what's next from <A href="/exhibitorDirectory/default.asp">2,700 consumer technology companies</A>. <BR><BR><STRONG>S1 Audio: Changing the Way You Hear Things<BR></STRONG><IMG height=153 hspace=8 src="/images/photos/S1_Audio_Image.jpg" width=288 align=right vspace=5>S1 Audio will demo some of the most unique audio products to be developed in years at the 2009 International CES. The first, called Bud-Bud, is essentially two earbuds in one. This means that splitters are no longer necessary to transfer from a mono phone conversation (one bud) to listening to music in stereo (two buds). Another version of Bud-Bud eliminates the common scene of two people sharing one pair of earbuds on trains, planes, etc. by quickly turning two earbuds into four. <BR><BR>The second product, called NxSet, changes the way people listen to music by placing the sound source around the neck. This adds an element of style and sharability to portable music (a group of friends walking down the street can hear music from the same source), almost like the modern day boom-box! It also increases the safety element for joggers, skateboarders, etc. because they can still hear outside noises.<BR><BR>Check out these new innovative ways to listen in LVCC, Central Hall, Booth # 11717. <BR>
